  "body": "### Component\n\nAnvil\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [ ] Foundry\n- [ ] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\n_No response_\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Operating System\n\n_No response_\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nAfter lowering the polling interval in #1667 we saw fork test run forever.\r\n\r\nthere's a deadlock that happens in fork mode, similar to the issues we were facing in #1549 #1037\r\n\r\nthat is because, tokio tasks are not supposed to block, because this prevents the scheduler from  moving the task to a blocking thread and might hinder other tasks from completing.\r\n\r\nsame thing happens within backend functions that have this pattern:\r\n\r\n```rust\r\n\r\nif let Some(mined) = self.mined_tx(..) {\r\n   return mined\r\n} \r\n\r\nif let Some(fork) = self.fork(){ \r\n   fork.get_tx().await\r\n}\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\nin order to serve a request for `mined`, we need access to the storage, this is when the deadlock can happen:\r\n\r\n1. a new block is being build (requires write lock of `storage`)\r\n2. a `eth_getTransactionByHash` is received that requires read lock of `storage`\r\n3. we try to acquire the read lock within an async function, which prevents the block from being built because the blocking task prevents the forked backend from being polled... \r\n4. deadlock: evm is waiting for data from the forked backend task which is not being polled because the rwlock::read blocks the task\r\n\r\nthis could be solved by switching to `tokio::sync::RwLock`, but hotfix is to wrap them in `spawn_blocking`",
